Absydian
Hi everyone!

I know a few people have been talking about doing something like this, a lot of people think its a good idea and some people are opposed, but hear me out! What I'm proposing, the Massive Mush Move is to Mush, what the Mega meta Jump is to Die2Nite. I will try and organize it if there is enough interest, so please use this thread to voice your opinions, whether you can't wait to take part, or if you think I'm wasting my time for whatever reason, please let me know here!

So here's the plan; Every month, let's say the first Saturday of every month, everyone who wants to join an active ship gets together on an IRC room, then we all hit the "start ship button" at pretty much the same time. And that's it! This would greatly increase the chances of landing in a ship full of active people who actually want to play, and who will log in regularly.

For this to work properly, I have outlined these basic rules, to make sure that this will leave a positive impression on the game and its community:
Everyone is welcome! That's right, invite any who enjoys playing mush, so long as they are willing to log in at least once a day, then spread the word and get them to join!
No side-swapping; Obviously normal game rules apply, but I just wanted to re-iterate this point, so even if you have been waiting for ages for a decent ship that you want to make go far, then you go and roll mush when you join the MMM ship, you HAVE to play as mush. This jump is for active people who want a challenging mush opponent, not necessarily a long-lasting ship.
Complete anonymity; Again, normal game rules apply, so don't reveal your name, or anyone else's, or go onto the forum and talk about what is going on in a ship in progress. If someone knows who you are they can 'cheat' the system and use this information to find out whether you are mush or not.
Every month! If this is to be a success it needs to be regular; something for everyone to look forward to. Some people have suggested it be bi-weekly, but monthly seems best to me: plenty of time for a long lasting ship to come to an end and still time to join a few less-active ships where people will be able to meet new active players and spread the word about the next MMM!

It'd be interesting to see mush skills specifically designed to add a thick layer of paranoia on the crew, and eliminating the validity of the process of elimination.

Hypochondriac: For one AP, you come down with a random illness/mental condition that can be 'cured', even though it does nothing to you. No longer would randomly contracting a disease prove humanity.

Glutton: For one AP, you can force yourself to eat an article of food even though you're full, but still gain nothing from it. This would eliminate food tests being practical, and adds the ability to consume ALL THE RATIONS with some setup.

[7950824]

A 3 person expo, with a planet of 9 zones or less with the zones Mountain, Cavern, and Predators on the list: the odds that all three of those zones will give an accident result and the accident will happen to the same person:

If expo team doesn't have a diplomat:
0.44 x 0.326 x 0.317 x .3333 = 1.5%

If expo team does have a diplomat:
0.44 x 0.326 x 0.487 x .3333 = 2.3%

I try hard to get my ships' teams to avoid any expo with a cumulative risk of death from any cause that is higher than 5%. Keep in mind too, that a zone like low temps has a 3% chance to kill a player all by itself, through getting lost and found dead:

20% chance to get lost; if lost 15% chance to be found dead: .2 x .15 = 3.0% chance to die from that zone alone.

A planet with 3 low temp zones; the odds for one or more players to die from getting lost in those zones is the odds of not getting lost and found dead multipled to each other (that's the odds that no one gets lost AND dies) - 100% (and then absolute value it), or:

.97 x .97 x .97 = |91.3% - 100%| = 8.7%. That's a deadly planet, for anyone without the compass, that's just 3 zones and doesn't even look at damage from other zones or that damage getting concentrated among the not-lost people.


Statistics can make one very nervous.... or confident.

Hrm. So castings are a way to for sure only a specific pool of players, with no chance of playing beside someone not on that list.

And, for those who care about achievements (Does this include glory rankings and supernovas and such?), castings give almost nothing. (There are achievements for cycles played as a character, but most of the achievements cannot be gained in casting - from what I understand)

Random jumps are for playing with whomever else happens to be around, could be any sort of others!

And planned jumps, such as MMM and Mushday, and various group jumps outside of castings, are a way of 'stacking the deck' of ships partially, mostly, or maybe completely filled with experienced players.

As I see it, MMM and other planned jumps still have a place in the game. You're likely to have a lean time as a large number of players initially focus on castings, but I bet you a good number of players will be returning to non-casting jumps over time. Either they run out of tickets at the moment, they decide they want to earn more achievements, they decide that they sometimes have fun in a more random sort of ship, or for many other reasons, I expect we have not seen the end of need for MMM.

How you time your jumps may change, and of course, 'right now' you're likely to have a time when few are involved, because they're involved with the new toy. But I'll be astonished if we've seen the last of you MMMers.

I've just random jumped (again), and this is my first ship after the castings update.

It's great.

It's been slower to fill than most of my ships, we're still waiting for one more. There's a LOT of talkative newbies, discussing the game, their curiosity and interest, and how to figure out what to do. There's several more experienced players on it. They're friendly and helpful. There's some talk about education happening in PMs, but the main threads are full of discussion about the game and how to start play.

The feel of the ship is highly friendly. It's rare in my experience to find even 3 talkative new players - this ship has no fewer than 8 (if I can count that high.... I think it's at least 8 ) players who said some form of 'Hi this is my first game' to 'I've only played this character once before, what do I do?' And there's conversations and nice attitudes from experienced and inexperienced all over the place.

Sample sizes of 1 are nearly worthless.... however. I must say, if -this- is what suffering looks like on random ships.... Bring it. We can endure any amount of this type of 'suffering'.

Sure, the ship's a bit slow to fill, been filling for 10 cycles now. 15 aboard and only 3 in bed; only 4 in camera rooms. This is gonna be an adventure in learning for sure.

But it's not terrible. It's not bad. It's really a stretch to call this 'suffering' at all, really. We're going to have problems, but we're going to have fun too, and what ship doesn't have problems? Solving problems is part of the fun, most ships.

So yeah, pity us random jumpers, stuck having a great time with well mannered and eager newbies. You'll be straining to reach D30 and get to Eden; Probably feeling disappointed with 'just winning' if that's all you get to do. Meanwhile, we'll be laughing together over how to learn how to play and what to do as each character and with each new problem we see, and will probably feel accomplished to have our ship end on D8 or so, with a lot of smiling players eager to jump on their next ship.... while you guys pity us, talk about how rough them random ships must be, and strain and worry to handle hunters while digging for starmaps.

Yeah, we randomers, we got it rough. You just keep telling yourselves that

Gather your courage. Be a good sport. If you're a Mush, try to be a strong villain, even if you dislike the role, as those are necessary to flavour the human heroism. If you're a human, cherish the athmosphere, the intrigue and paranoia: don't be quick on performing tests and such on yourself, and never do so on others. Cooperate, yet be patient to those who can't. MMM gathers all levels of skill, activity and timezone, so it's natural that someone could be a noob. Educate them and respect them. Think about your crewmates as of actual people, not pixel figures, because they are.
Everything depends on you. That's the actual point of the game, after all.

There is still time. Post announcements in your casting forums. PM your friends. Re-read the rules. Re-read them again. They're there to make the experience generally better, not more stiff. If you're into it, think about the roleplay you could perform, but if you aren't, it's okay.

May this event become a good shared memory.
